SIMPLE: tributary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tributary
<hw>Trib"u*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tributaire</ets>, F. <ets>tributaire</ets>, L.
<ets>tributarius</ets>. See <er>Tribute</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Paying tribute to another, either from compulsion, as an
acknowledgment of submission, or to secure protection, or for the
purpose of purchasing peace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Julius] unto Rome made them <qex>tributary</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, subject; subordinate; inferior.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He to grace his <qex>tributary</qex> gods.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Paid in tribute.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Tributary</xex>
tears.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Yielding supplies of any kind; serving to form or
make up, a greater object of the same kind, as a part, branch, etc.;
contributing; <as>as, the Ohio has many <ex>tributary</ex> streams, and
is itself <ex>tributary</ex> to the Mississippi</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1537 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tributary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tributary
<hw>Trib"u*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Tributaries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A ruler or
state that pays tribute, or a stated sum, to a conquering power, for the
purpose of securing peace and protection, or as an acknowledgment of
submission, or for the purchase of security.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stream or river flowing into a larger river or
into a lake; an affluent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tribute</ent>⟦br⟧
